"Tendring, Essex, England":"英國艾可騰德林","lifeSummary":"當Phillip Atta Stone於1265年出生在英國艾可格亞特 布羅姆利時，他的父親Walter Atte Stone25歲，母親Unknown Unknown25歲。他於大約1284年與Stone在英國結婚。他們至少是1個兒子的父母。他去世於1315年在英國哈普爾本特利享年50歲。"},"zh-hans":{"1265–1315":"1265年–1315年","1260–1310":"1260年–1310年","1285–1327":"1285年–1327年","1240–1269":"1240年–1269年","1240–1278":"1240年–1278年","1285":"1285年","1240":"1240年","1260":"1260年","1290":"1290年","1327":"1327年","1315":"1315年","1269":"1269年","1278":"1278年","1310":"1310年","1265":"1265年","about 1278":"大约1278年","about 1284":"大约1284年","about 1285":"大约1285年","1317":"1317年","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"英国哈普爾本特利","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"英国艾可格亞特 布羅姆利","England":"英国","Tendring, Essex, England":"英国艾可騰德林","lifeSummary":"当Phillip Atta Stone于1265年出生在英国艾可格亞特 布羅姆利时，他的父亲Walter Atte Stone25岁，母亲Unknown Unknown25岁。他于大约1284年与Stone在英国结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世于1315年在英国哈普爾本特利享年50岁。"},"hr":{"1265–1315":"1265.–1315.","1260–1310":"1260–1310.","1285–1327":"1285–1327","1240–1269":"1240–1269.","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315.","1269":"1269.","1278":"1278","1310":"1310.","1265":"1265.","about 1278":"oko 1278.","about 1284":"oko 1284.","about 1285":"oko 1285.","1317":"1317","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","England":"England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England"},"cs":{"1265–1315":"1265–1315","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1285–1327":"1285–1327","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","about 1278":"okolo 1278","about 1284":"okolo 1284","about 1285":"okolo 1285","1317":"1317","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, Anglie","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, Anglie","England":"Anglie","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, Anglie"},"da":{"1265–1315":"1265–1315","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1285–1327":"1285–1327","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","about 1278":"omkring 1278","about 1284":"omkring 1284","about 1285":"omkring 1285","1317":"1317","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","England":"England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England"},"nl":{"1265–1315":"1265–1315","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1285–1327":"1285–1327","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","about 1278":"circa 1278","about 1284":"circa 1284","about 1285":"circa 1285","1317":"1317","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","England":"England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England"},"en":{"1265–1315":"1265–1315","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1285–1327":"1285–1327","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","about 1278":"about 1278","about 1284":"about 1284","about 1285":"about 1285","1317":"1317","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"Bentley, Hampshire, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","England":"England","Tendring, Essex, England":"Tendring, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone, rock’ (Old English <i>stān</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on stony ground, by a notable outcrop of rock, or by a stone boundary-marker or monument, or habitational, from a place called Stone, such as those in Buckinghamshire, Devon, Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Somerset, Staffordshire, and Worcestershire.","Irish (Kilkenny): adopted for Irish <b>Ó Clochartaigh</b> (see   Clougherty  ) and/or <b>Ó Clochasaigh</b> (see   Clohessy  ), and possibly several other names containing or thought to contain the element <i>cloch</i> ‘stone’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of various surnames in other languages, meaning ‘stone’, including Jewish   Stein  , Norwegian <b>Steine</b>, French   Lapierre  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stoner","meanings":["English (Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone’ + <i>-er</i>, used for someone who lived by a prominent rock or stone, or perhaps who came from a place called Stone, although this formation is more rare. See   Stone   and compare   Stoneman  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Steiner  ."]},{"name":"Stones","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Stone   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. A number of the places called Stone are sometimes recorded with plural spellings in the medieval period, including Stone (Staffordshire), recorded as <i>Stanes</i> in 1187."]},{"name":"Stenner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt.","German: occupational name for a stonemason or stonecutter, or a topographic name for someone who lived on stony ground, from a derivative of Middle High German <i>stein</i> ‘stone’, ‘stony place’. Compare   Stone   and   Stein  .","English: variant of   Stayner  ."]},{"name":"Clougherty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aileen.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Clochartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Clochartach</i>’, a personal name, probably formed with <i>cloch</i> ‘stone’,   Stone   being an alternative Anglicized form of the surname."]},{"name":"Roach","meanings":["English:","of Norman origin, from Old French and Middle English <i>roche</i> ‘rock, cliff, promontory’, sometimes a translation of   Stone  . The surname may have been topographic, denoting someone who lived on or by a prominent rock or rocky place, or a habitational name for someone who lived or came from a place so named, such as one of those called Roque or Roche(s) in Normandy and neighboring regions, or Roche in Cornwall, Roach Farm in Clyst Hydon (Devon), or Roch in Pembrokeshire (see   Roch  ).","in Lancashire perhaps referring to the River Roch, which runs through Rochdale; the river name is probably a back-formation from <i>Recedham</i>, an early name for Rochdale recorded in 1086, derived from Old English <i>reced</i> ‘building, house, hall’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’. Alternatively, the Lancashire name could be a shortened form of the now rare or extinct surname <b>Rochdale</b> alias <b>Rachedale</b>, <i>Rachdall</i>, a habitational name from Rochdale (Lancashire). From the 18th century onward the name is difficult to distinguish from   Roch  , borne by Irish migrants to South Lancashire, especially Liverpool."]},{"name":"Stoneman","meanings":["English: perhaps an occupational name for someone who was the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of a person surnamed   Stone  . Alternatively, the name may have been an alias of   Stone  , used for someone who lived by a prominent stone or rock or at a minor place so named (Middle English <i>ston</i> + <i>man</i>).","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name for someone who worked with stone or who sold precious stones; a jeweler.","English: perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Ston(e)man</i> (Old English <i>Stān(e)mann</i>), a pet form of Old English personal names beginning with <i>Stān-</i> (from the word ‘stone’, ‘rock’) + the Old English hypocoristic suffix <i>-mann</i>."]}]},{"name":"Phillip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Philip  , in part a reflection of the surname, which is usually spelled <i>Phillips</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Atta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Ásta</i>, from <i>ást</i> ‘love‘."],"variants":[{"name":"Astrid","meanings":["name, derived from Old Norse <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>fríðr</i> ‘fair, beautiful’. It came into use in the English-speaking world during the 20th century, influenced to some extent by  Queen Astrid  of the Belgians (  1905–35 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":50,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Phillip Atta Stone was born in 1265, in Great Bromley, Essex, England, his father, Walter Atte Stone, was 25 and his mother, Unknown Unknown, was 25. He married Stone about 1284, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1315, in Bentley, Hampshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1265–1315":"1265–1315","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1285–1327":"1285–1327","1240–1269":"1240–1269","1240–1278":"1240–1278","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1269":"1269","1278":"1278","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","about 1278":"umbes 1278","about 1284":"umbes 1284","about 1285":"umbes 1285","1317":"1317","Bentley, Hampshire, England":"